{"parse":{"title":"Cholera belt","pageid":44397719,"revid":828317653,"text":{"*":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><p class=\"mw-empty-elt\">\n</p>\n<div class=\"thumb tright\"><div class=\"thumbinner\" style=\"width:172px;\"><a href=\"/wiki/File:Cholera_belt.jpg\" class=\"image\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/e/e2/Cholera_belt.jpg/170px-Cholera_belt.jpg\" width=\"170\" height=\"391\" class=\"thumbimage\" srcset=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/e/e2/Cholera_belt.jpg/255px-Cholera_belt.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/e/e2/Cholera_belt.jpg 2x\" data-file-width=\"265\" data-file-height=\"609\" /></a>  <div class=\"thumbcaption\"><div class=\"magnify\"><a href=\"/wiki/File:Cholera_belt.jpg\" class=\"internal\" title=\"Enlarge\"></a></div>1914 advertisement</div></div></div>\n<p>A <b>cholera belt</b> was a flat strip of (usually red) <a href=\"/wiki/Flannel\" title=\"Flannel\">flannel</a> or knitted wool about six feet long and six inches wide which was twisted around the abdomen before wearing a shirt and purported to be a preventive measure against <a href=\"/wiki/Cholera\" title=\"Cholera\">cholera</a>. It was a standard army issue and widely believed to protect the wearer from cholera, <a href=\"/wiki/Dysentery\" title=\"Dysentery\">dysentery</a> and other ills thought to be brought about by chilling of the abdomen. Their use continued well after the causal agent of cholera was established.<sup id=\"cite_ref-hist_1-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-hist-1\">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup> In 1848 the instructions to army medical officers in India included the suggestion that every soldier should be provided two \"cholera belts\". In the early 1900s, its use was still recommended for preventing dysentery.<sup id=\"cite_ref-hist_1-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-hist-1\">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup> In 1914, donations by the tiny village of <a href=\"/wiki/Middlemarch,_New_Zealand\" title=\"Middlemarch, New Zealand\">Middlemarch</a>, <a href=\"/wiki/New_Zealand\" title=\"New Zealand\">New Zealand</a> of items such as tobacco, shirts and tinned fruit for soldiers going to fight in <a href=\"/wiki/World_War_I\" title=\"World War I\">World War I</a>, included \"26 cholera belts\".<sup id=\"cite_ref-2\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-2\">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup> The idea of abdominal chilling as a factor in illness was brought up as late as 1947<sup id=\"cite_ref-3\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-3\">&#91;3&#93;</a></sup> although it was rejoined by those who pointed out that the idea was not based on experimental evidence.<sup id=\"cite_ref-4\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-4\">&#91;4&#93;</a></sup>\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"References\">References</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Cholera_belt&amp;action=edit&amp;section=1\" title=\"Edit section: References\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<div class=\"reflist\" style=\"list-style-type: decimal;\">\n<div class=\"mw-references-wrap\"><ol class=\"references\">\n<li id=\"cite_note-hist-1\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\">^ <a href=\"#cite_ref-hist_1-0\"><sup><i><b>a</b></i></sup></a> <a href=\"#cite_ref-hist_1-1\"><sup><i><b>b</b></i></sup></a></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><cite class=\"citation journal\">Renbourn, E.T. (1957). <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"//www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC1034286\">\"The history of the flannel binder and cholera belt\"</a>. <i>Medical History</i>. <b>1</b> (3): 211\u2013225. <a href=\"/wiki/Digital_object_identifier\" title=\"Digital object identifier\">doi</a>:<a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"//doi.org/10.1017/S0025727300021281\">10.1017/S0025727300021281</a>. <a href=\"/wiki/PubMed_Central\" title=\"PubMed Central\">PMC</a>&#160;<span class=\"plainlinks\"><a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"//www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC1034286\">1034286</a>&#8239;<img alt=\"Freely accessible\" src=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/6/65/Lock-green.svg/9px-Lock-green.svg.png\" title=\"Freely accessible\" width=\"9\" height=\"14\" srcset=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/6/65/Lock-green.svg/14px-Lock-green.svg.png 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/6/65/Lock-green.svg/18px-Lock-green.svg.png 2x\" data-file-width=\"512\" data-file-height=\"813\" /></span>. <a href=\"/wiki/PubMed_Identifier\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"PubMed Identifier\">PMID</a>&#160;<a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"//www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/13440256\">13440256</a>.</cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal&amp;rft.genre=article&amp;rft.jtitle=Medical+History&amp;rft.atitle=The+history+of+the+flannel+binder+and+cholera+belt&amp;rft.volume=1&amp;rft.issue=3&amp;rft.pages=211-225&amp;rft.date=1957&amp;rft_id=%2F%2Fwww.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov%2Fpmc%2Farticles%2FPMC1034286&amp;rft_id=info%3Apmid%2F13440256&amp;rft_id=info%3Adoi%2F10.1017%2FS0025727300021281&amp;rft.au=Renbourn%2C+E.T.&amp;rft_id=%2F%2Fwww.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov%2Fpmc%2Farticles%2FPMC1034286&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3ACholera+belt\" class=\"Z3988\"><span style=\"display:none;\">&#160;</span></span></span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-2\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-2\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\">Cited on p. 4, Taieri Pet, Newsletter for Middlemarch area, 1 August 1914</span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-3\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-3\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><cite class=\"citation journal\">Kershaw, G.R. (1947). <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"//www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC2053389\">\"Acute non-specific diarrhoea and dysentery. Local chilling of the abdomen as a causative factor\"</a>. <i>British Medical Journal</i>. <b>1</b> (4507): 717\u2013719. <a href=\"/wiki/Digital_object_identifier\" title=\"Digital object identifier\">doi</a>:<a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"//doi.org/10.1136/bmj.1.4507.717\">10.1136/bmj.1.4507.717</a>. <a href=\"/wiki/PubMed_Central\" title=\"PubMed Central\">PMC</a>&#160;<span class=\"plainlinks\"><a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"//www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC2053389\">2053389</a>&#8239;<img alt=\"Freely accessible\" src=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/6/65/Lock-green.svg/9px-Lock-green.svg.png\" title=\"Freely accessible\" width=\"9\" height=\"14\" srcset=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/6/65/Lock-green.svg/14px-Lock-green.svg.png 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/6/65/Lock-green.svg/18px-Lock-green.svg.png 2x\" data-file-width=\"512\" data-file-height=\"813\" /></span>. <a href=\"/wiki/PubMed_Identifier\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"PubMed Identifier\">PMID</a>&#160;<a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"//www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/20248097\">20248097</a>.</cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal&amp;rft.genre=article&amp;rft.jtitle=British+Medical+Journal&amp;rft.atitle=Acute+non-specific+diarrhoea+and+dysentery.+Local+chilling+of+the+abdomen+as+a+causative+factor&amp;rft.volume=1&amp;rft.issue=4507&amp;rft.pages=717-719&amp;rft.date=1947&amp;rft_id=%2F%2Fwww.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov%2Fpmc%2Farticles%2FPMC2053389&amp;rft_id=info%3Apmid%2F20248097&amp;rft_id=info%3Adoi%2F10.1136%2Fbmj.1.4507.717&amp;rft.au=Kershaw%2C+G.R.&amp;rft_id=%2F%2Fwww.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov%2Fpmc%2Farticles%2FPMC2053389&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3ACholera+belt\" class=\"Z3988\"><span style=\"display:none;\">&#160;</span></span></span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-4\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-4\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><cite class=\"citation journal\">Smith, G.L.Morgan (1947). <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"//www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC2055274\">\"Correspondence. Acute non-specific diarrhoea and dysentery\"</a>. <i>British Medical Journal</i>. <b>2</b> (4517): 189. <a href=\"/wiki/Digital_object_identifier\" title=\"Digital object identifier\">doi</a>:<a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"//doi.org/10.1136/bmj.2.4517.189-a\">10.1136/bmj.2.4517.189-a</a>. <a href=\"/wiki/PubMed_Central\" title=\"PubMed Central\">PMC</a>&#160;<span class=\"plainlinks\"><a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"//www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC2055274\">2055274</a>&#8239;<img alt=\"Freely accessible\" src=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/6/65/Lock-green.svg/9px-Lock-green.svg.png\" title=\"Freely accessible\" width=\"9\" height=\"14\" srcset=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/6/65/Lock-green.svg/14px-Lock-green.svg.png 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/6/65/Lock-green.svg/18px-Lock-green.svg.png 2x\" data-file-width=\"512\" data-file-height=\"813\" /></span>. <a href=\"/wiki/PubMed_Identifier\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"PubMed Identifier\">PMID</a>&#160;<a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"//www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/20255535\">20255535</a>.</cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal&amp;rft.genre=article&amp;rft.jtitle=British+Medical+Journal&amp;rft.atitle=Correspondence.+Acute+non-specific+diarrhoea+and+dysentery&amp;rft.volume=2&amp;rft.issue=4517&amp;rft.pages=189&amp;rft.date=1947&amp;rft_id=%2F%2Fwww.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov%2Fpmc%2Farticles%2FPMC2055274&amp;rft_id=info%3Apmid%2F20255535&amp;rft_id=info%3Adoi%2F10.1136%2Fbmj.2.4517.189-a&amp;rft.au=Smith%2C+G.L.Morgan&amp;rft_id=%2F%2Fwww.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov%2Fpmc%2Farticles%2FPMC2055274&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AC